## Audience 2: Clinical and Administrative Staff

Clinical and administrative staff who use OpenMRS do not need — and should not receive — the technical details of the authorization package. But they do need to know three things:

First, the system they are using to document patient care has been formally evaluated and authorized. This is a trust signal — staff should feel confident that the system protecting their patients' information has been subjected to rigorous security review.

Second, the security program places responsibilities on all users: reporting suspected security incidents, completing annual security training, following the access management policies for account use and sharing. These responsibilities existed before the authorization, but the ATO is a natural moment to reinforce them.

Third, there is a plan for what happens if the system is unavailable. The clinical downtime procedures are in development — clinical staff should know this work is in progress and that they will receive training on downtime procedures when the procedures are finalized.

The ISSO and Health IT Manager jointly drafted a brief all-staff communication:

---

**ALL-STAFF COMMUNICATION**
**From:** Health IT Manager and Information Security Lead
**Subject:** OpenMRS Security Authorization Complete

We want to share an important update on the security status of our OpenMRS electronic health record system.

Our OpenMRS system has completed a formal security authorization process, including an independent review of all the security controls protecting your patients' information — encryption, access controls, monitoring, and incident response. The system has been formally authorized to operate.

A few important reminders for all staff:

If you observe something that seems like a security problem — unusual system behavior, a request to share your login credentials, a message that seems suspicious — please report it to [contact] immediately. Our incident response plan means every report gets taken seriously.

All staff are required to complete the annual security awareness training. Current completion status will be reviewed quarterly.

We are also working on formal procedures for how to continue patient care documentation if the EHR system is temporarily unavailable. Training on those procedures will be provided when they are finalized in the coming weeks. In the meantime, if you have questions about what to do during a system outage, please contact [Health IT Manager contact].

Thank you for the role you play every day in protecting our patients' information.

