## Audience 3: System Registry and Organizational Risk Dashboard

Every organization should maintain an inventory of its authorized systems — a registry that enables leadership to understand the authorization status, risk posture, and upcoming re-authorization requirements for all systems at a glance. For a large federal agency, this is a formal GRC platform entry. For a small clinic, it may be a maintained spreadsheet or a section in a risk management tool.

The system registry entry for the OpenMRS authorization:

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| System Name | MyClinic OpenMRS EHR |
| System ID | MCOPENMRS-001 |
| System Owner | Health IT Manager |
| ISSO | Information Security Lead |
| Authorizing Official | Executive Director |
| Authorization Date | [date] |
| Authorization Expiration | [date + 3 years] |
| Impact Level | HIGH |
| Authorization Status | AUTHORIZED — CONDITIONAL |
| Open Conditions | Condition 1 (CP-2) — 90 days; 3 others ongoing |
| Open POA&M Items | 10 (1 Moderate, 9 Low) |
| Next AO Touchpoint | 45-day check-in [specific date] |
| Next Quarterly POA&M Report Due | [date + 90 days] |
| Re-authorization Planning Start | [date + 2 years 9 months] |
| Authorization Package Location | [document repository path] |
| Notes | First formal RMF authorization for this system |

**Re-authorization planning reminder:** The ISSO added a calendar entry for [authorization date + 2 years 9 months] — three months before the authorization expiration date — to begin the re-authorization planning process. Re-authorization is not a repeat of the initial authorization from scratch; it is a structured review of what has changed in the system, the threat environment, and the organization's risk posture, followed by an updated assessment and a new AO decision. Starting three months before expiration allows enough time to complete the process without operating on an expired ATO.

