## Scheduling the Re-authorization Cycle

One of the most common failures in security authorization programs is treating the three-year authorization period as a period of inactivity between authorization events — and then scrambling to produce a re-authorization package in the final weeks before expiration.

The continuous monitoring program prevents the security posture from degrading silently during the authorization period. But re-authorization also requires updating the authorization documentation to reflect what has changed — new POA&M items added, old ones closed, system changes documented, threat environment updated, and a new independent assessment conducted.

For MyClinic, the re-authorization planning timeline:

| Milestone | Target Date |
|---|---|
| Re-authorization planning begins | [authorization date + 33 months] |
| SSP currency review — major update if needed | [authorization date + 36 months - 6 weeks] |
| New assessment engagement contracted | [authorization date + 33 months] |
| New assessment conducted | [authorization date + 35 months] |
| New authorization package assembled | [authorization date + 35.5 months] |
| New AO review and decision | [authorization date + 36 months] |

Building this timeline into the system registry now — as a series of calendar events with responsible parties — means the re-authorization process begins when planned rather than when the expiration date appears unexpectedly.

