## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The archival package README concept — a plain-language orientation guide for future reviewers — was directly shaped by reflecting on the **2015 OPM data breach** from the institutional continuity perspective.

The OPM breach involved attackers who had persistent access to OPM networks for over a year before detection. Post-breach analysis found that the security documentation for affected systems was fragmented, inconsistent, and in some cases out of date. Congressional testimony suggested that the security team had knowledge of vulnerabilities that was not consistently documented in ways that transferred across personnel changes.

One of the recommendations that emerged from the OPM breach investigation was that federal agencies needed to maintain security documentation as operational institutional memory, not just as compliance artifacts — documentation that a new ISSO could use to understand the system's security posture without requiring months of oral history from the prior ISSO.

The README document in MyClinic's archival package is a small-clinic implementation of that principle. MyClinic cannot afford the deep security bench that large agencies have. The README acknowledges that reality and addresses it: if the ISSO departs, the documentation should carry enough context that the security program can continue without a lengthy knowledge transfer conversation that may never happen.

This is the difference between documentation that satisfies a requirement and documentation that serves the organization.

