## What I Am Still Thinking About

The all-staff communication today included a note that clinical downtime procedures training will be provided "in the coming weeks." That framing is accurate — the 90-day CP-2 deadline means training is coming — but it creates an expectation among clinical staff that the ISSO and Health IT Manager now need to deliver on.

I want to make sure there is a feedback loop between the CP-2 milestone progress and the staff communication. If the 90-day deadline slips — which is the risk the AO established a 45-day check-in specifically to prevent — clinical staff who are expecting training in "the coming weeks" will eventually notice the training hasn't appeared. That creates a credibility gap between the security team's communications and the organization's actual execution.

The 45-day check-in needs to include a specific review of the clinical staff communication — if the CP-2 procedures are on track, a more specific training timeline can be communicated to staff. If the procedures are behind, the communication should be updated honestly rather than allowed to sit as an outdated promise. Trust is built incrementally through accurate communication, not through optimistic commitments that the organization then quietly misses.

